{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486727"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"164"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582455"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"164"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/164"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.8,0.08,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107269"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/164"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89729"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1239"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"4795"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6399"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44450"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107269"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of sudden onset right-sided testicular pain. He has vomited once and feels nauseated. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 112/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Examination of the scrotum reveals a normal left testis with intact cremasteric reflex. The right testis is exquisitely tender to palpation, swollen and high-riding with the cremasteric reflex absent on this side. Urinalysis is negative for blood, leukocytes, and nitrites.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent scrotal ultrasound with doppler studies","Surgical exploration of the scrotum","Oral antibiotics and urology referral","Manual detorsion followed by elective orchidopexy","Intravenous analgesia and anti-emetics"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a TWIST score of 5 (2 points for testicular swelling, 1 point for absent cremasteric reflex, 1 point for nausea/vomiting, 1 point for high-riding testis), indicating a high risk of testicular torsion. Until proven otherwise, acute scrotal pain with high clinical suspicion for torsion should be treated as a surgical emergency. The presence of nausea and vomiting further increases the probability of torsion. Any delay in recognising this problem and taking appropriate action is likely to lead to infarction of the affected testis. The most expeditious step is immediate \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical exploration of the scrotum\u003C/strong\u003E. Given that the onset of pain was four hours ago, the viability of the testis could already be compromised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile an \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Escrotal ultrasound with doppler studies\u003C/strong\u003E may demonstrate decreased blood flow to the affected testis, this investigation should never delay surgical management when there is a high clinical suspicion for torsion based on history and physical examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics and urology referral\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for epididymitis, but the acute onset of severe pain, high-riding testis, and absent cremasteric reflex make testicular torsion much more likely than infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManual detorsion followed by elective orchidopexy\u003C/strong\u003E may be attempted in some cases, but given the duration of symptoms and high clinical suspicion, immediate surgical exploration is more appropriate to assess testicular viability and perform definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous analgesia and anti-emetics\u003C/strong\u003E would provide symptomatic relief, this approach does not address the underlying cause and risks further ischaemic damage to the testis from the suspected torsion. Prompt surgical exploration is still warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Good clinical evidence of testicular torsion should be followed by prompt surgical exploration.","The TWIST score is a clinical prediction tool that can help identify patients at high risk of testicular torsion who require urgent surgical exploration.","Imaging should not delay surgical management when clinical suspicion for testicular torsion is high."],"references":["Bourke M M, Silverberg JZ. Acute Scrotal Emergencies. Emerg Med Clin N Am 2019; 37:593-610. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31563197/","Choudhury P, Saroya KK, Anand S, Agarwal P, Jain V, Dhua AK, et al. Unjumbling the TWIST score for testicular torsion: systematic review and meta-analysis. Pediatr Surg Int. 2023;39(1):137. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36811717/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89729"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"164"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89729"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T10:37:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T10:38:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"164"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107269"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings"